{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"coaching":[{"coaching":"Pin down the AC2 jq event-uuid proving command with a concrete worked example.","decision":"block","finding_refs":["f551c0d14c9a959cd","fc708d1af1a1e690b","fdcaaca7dac96a75f","fc6568c0e21b76f1e","f80d887127cd08701"],"move_id":"6","move_name":"specification by example","subject":"the AC2 jq event-uuid proving command"},{"coaching":"Realign canary workflow coverage versus parent epic scope to the parent's plan — the parent wins on conflict; if the parent is genuinely wrong, update the PARENT first (which forces its re-review), never silently diverge the leaf.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["faeac75fcd81073b2"],"move_id":"13","move_name":"realign to parent plan","subject":"canary workflow coverage versus parent epic scope"},{"coaching":"Plan how canary fallback proof path specification will be verified in-session — restate any deferred or unobservable success target as an observable proxy.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["f4eea01b111a4212e","fdaf9a5c472c78ce3","f796e920e3e08d54c","fe92d5ab1e3a56255","f44c8e035e069cf01"],"move_id":"9","move_name":"plan the verification","subject":"canary fallback proof path specification"},{"coaching":"Run a quick pre-mortem on secret overwrite rollback and back-out path: how could this plan fail?","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["f065df51e0e05a7f2"],"move_id":"3","move_name":"pre-mortem","subject":"secret overwrite rollback and back-out path"},{"coaching":"Pin down required IAM principal and SSM permission scope with a concrete worked example.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["f261b2dc4db92a7c6"],"move_id":"6","move_name":"specification by example","subject":"required IAM principal and SSM permission scope"},{"coaching":"Plan how SSM-to-GitHub secret rotation and re-sync lifecycle will be verified in-session — restate any deferred or unobservable success target as an observable proxy.","decision":"advisory","finding_refs":["fc555b73a5feba01b"],"move_id":"9","move_name":"plan the verification","subject":"SSM-to-GitHub secret rotation and re-sync lifecycle"}],"coverage":{"counts":{"advisory_overflow":0,"advisory_surfaced":9,"blocking":3,"dropped":5,"indeterminate":0},"det":{"P1":{"ac_items":3,"blocking":false,"clarity_score":7,"name":"readiness-shape","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P2":{"blocking":false,"name":"resolution","probed":1,"ran":true,"references":1,"resolved":1,"status":"pass","unresolved_or_abstained":0},"P3":{"blocking":false,"name":"package-existence","packages":0,"ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P4":{"ac_items":3,"blocking":false,"desc_chars":4246,"file_impact":1,"name":"oversize","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P5":{"blocking":false,"children":0,"name":"task-dag","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P6":{"ac_items":3,"blocking":false,"name":"ac-quality","ran":true,"status":"pass","verify_commands_linted":46,"verify_lint_abstained":46},"P7":{"blocking":false,"destructive_hits":[],"name":"destructive-sniff","ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P8":{"blocking":false,"budget_tokens":868000,"name":"reviewability","plan_tokens":1083,"ran":true,"status":"pass"},"P9":{"applicable":true,"blocking":false,"file_impact":1,"name":"file-impact-coverage","ran":true,"status":"pass"}},"floored_criteria":["T10","T5c","T9"],"floored_finding_ids":["f261b2dc4db92a7c6","fcf71f7bf8c5335b1","fc555b73a5feba01b"],"llm_ran":true,"metrics":{"claim_path":"no-llm/no-network (structural; the fast claim check is a local HMAC verify)","det_ms":240.2,"llm_calls":29,"llm_ms":445268.7,"total_ms":445630.4,"verify_requests":23},"narrowed":true,"remediation":{"baseline":"signature","eligible":true,"reasons":{"code_unchanged":true,"plan_changed":true,"prior_sidecar":true,"registry_unchanged":true,"signed":true,"within_window":true}},"routing":{"agent_tier":["A1","E4","G1G2","G6","G7","T1","T10","T11","T13","T14","T3","T5c","T8","removal-rationale"],"single_turn":["COH","E1","E2","E3","E5","E6","F1","G5","T12","T2","T4","T5b","T5e","T6","T7","T9","hedge"]}},"findings":[{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Fix the AC2 proving command to dereference the shell variable holding the event uuid: replace `--arg u E` with `--arg u \"$E\"` (or whatever shell variable name is used to hold the recorded event uuid).","cohort":["G1G2"],"criteria":["G1G2"],"decision":"block","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan text: `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'`","jq `--arg name value` always takes a literal string value; to dereference a shell variable, the command must be `--arg u \"$E\"` or use `--argjson`","With `--arg u E`, `$u` is always the string literal \"E\", so the predicate is `all(.[]; .event_uuid != \"E\")` — true for any real uuid, making the gate trivially pass regardless of whether event E was actually verified"],"finding":"The AC2 proving command `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` passes the literal four-character string \"E\" as the jq variable `$u` (because `--arg u E` binds the text `E`, not the shell variable `$E`), so the check passes trivially for any run where no event has uuid literally \"E\" — the actual event uuid is never compared.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f551c0d14c9a959cd","impact":1.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — second AC bullet, proving command","norm_id":"nb33e20504164983c","priority":1.0,"reason":"high-priority+criterion-opted-in","scenarios":["Operator runs the command with the literal text substituted; the check exits 0 even if the real event is not in verified state, giving a false-positive proof of signing."],"severity":"critical","suggested_fix":"Replace:\n```\nrebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'\n```\nWith (assuming the event uuid is stored in shell variable `$E`):\n```\nrebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u \"$E\" -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'\n```","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"na","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"broken_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"high","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"high","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Fix the AC2 jq proving command so the shell variable holding the actual event uuid is interpolated into the jq invocation, e.g. replace `--arg u E` with `--arg u \"$E\"` (after assigning `E=<the recorded uuid>`) so the filter actually tests whether that specific uuid is absent from the non-verified report.","cohort":["G6"],"criteria":["G6"],"decision":"block","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan AC2 writes: `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` where 'E' is described as a placeholder for 'the event uuid'","jq manual: `--arg name value` binds the *literal string* value to $name; `--arg u E` binds $u to the literal 4-character string 'E', not a shell variable expansion","No `E=<uuid>` assignment appears anywhere in AC2 before the jq invocation; the shell variable $E is never populated","The same defect was identified in cached plan-reviews of sibling stories 1a51 and 4dc0 (`.rebar/cache/plan-review/1a51-b170-5168-46d2/6709f3fd88e8050bb0b1.json`, `.rebar/cache/plan-review/4dc0-d003-c236-45de/e03b70802ce46111012c.json`)","verify_authorship.py lines 498-504 confirm verified events are excluded from the report — the absence-based check is conceptually correct but only if the uuid is actually interpolated"],"finding":"The AC2 jq proving command `jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` is mechanically broken: jq's `--arg name value` syntax passes the *literal string* 'value' to `$name`, so `--arg u E` sets `$u` to the four-character string 'E', not the shell variable `$E`. Because no real event uuid equals 'E', the filter `all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)` is a tautology (always true) and exits 0 even if the target event IS present in the non-verified report — producing a guaranteed false-green verification with no diagnostic value.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fc708d1af1a1e690b","impact":1.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria → AC2 proving command: `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'`","norm_id":"n6ec6daa86c49cae4","priority":1.0,"reason":"high-priority+criterion-opted-in","scenarios":["Operator records event uuid (e.g. 'a1b2c3d4-5678-...'), runs the command verbatim; jq checks all(event_uuid != 'E') which is always true; exits 0 even if the event appears in the non-verified report","A signing misconfiguration produces an unsigned event; the proof step still exits 0, so the operator records a false-green attestation and the AC is marked satisfied despite signing being broken"],"severity":"critical","suggested_fix":"Record the event uuid first: `E=<the uuid from rebar show <t>>`, then run: `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u \"$E\" -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'`. The double-quoted shell expansion `\"$E\"` passes the variable's value as jq's argument string, not the literal character 'E'.","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"broken_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"high","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"high","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Fix the jq proving command to expand the shell variable: change `--arg u E` to `--arg u \"$E\"` (with double quotes so the shell expands `$E` to the actual UUID before jq receives it).","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"block","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["AC2 text: `jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` — the literal string 'E' is passed as $u, not the shell variable $E","jq manual: `--arg name value` binds `$name` to the string `value`; shell variable expansion requires quoting: `--arg u \"$E\"`","verify_identity_report.schema.json confirms `event_uuid` is a UUID string, which will always differ from the four-character literal 'E'"],"finding":"AC2's absence-from-report proving command `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` passes the literal four-character string `\"E\"` as jq's `$u` variable, not the shell variable holding the actual event UUID. jq's `--arg name value` syntax takes two positional words: `name=u`, `value=E` (the letter). Any real event UUID (e.g. `abc1-...`) trivially satisfies `!= 'E'`, so the command exits 0 regardless of whether the target event is verified — the proof is vacuously true.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fdcaaca7dac96a75f","impact":1.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC2: `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'`","norm_id":"n36e7e86c55aae57b","priority":1.0,"reason":"high-priority+criterion-opted-in","scenarios":["Operator records event UUID E=abc1-2345-..., runs the command as written, jq sees $u='E', every entry has .event_uuid != 'E' (trivially true), command exits 0 — but the event may actually be in the non-verified report (i.e. unverified), producing a false proof of signing"],"severity":"critical","suggested_fix":"Replace the command with: `E=<recorded-event-uuid>; rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u \"$E\" -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'`","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"na","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"broken_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"high","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"high","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Fix the jq proving command in AC2 to dereference the shell variable: replace `--arg u E` with `--arg u \"$E\"` so the command checks the actual event uuid, not the literal letter 'E'.","cohort":["E2","E6","F1"],"criteria":["E6"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan text: `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'`","jq --arg NAME VALUE syntax: VALUE is taken as a literal string, not a shell variable reference; to dereference a shell variable the form must be --arg u \"$E\" (with the dollar sign and quotes).","VERIFY-COMMAND DEFECT TAXONOMY type 2: shell-expansion leakage — a $VAR inside a jq --arg position expands before jq sees it only if properly quoted; the current form never expands the shell variable."],"finding":"The jq proving command in AC2 passes the literal string 'E' as the jq variable value rather than the shell variable's content: `jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` assigns $u = \"E\" (the letter), so the assertion checks that no event has uuid == 'E', which is always true and proves nothing. The correct form requires quoting the shell variable: `--arg u \"$E\"`.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fc6568c0e21b76f1e","impact":1.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — second AC bullet, proving command `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'`","norm_id":"nd811bbbfe0f46f69","priority":1.0,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["Executor runs the command with $E set to a real event uuid; the command silently checks uuid == 'E' (the letter), always exits 0, and falsely attests the event is verified — AC2 is satisfied by a do-nothing assertion."],"severity":"critical","suggested_fix":"```bash\nrebar verify-identity --all --format json \\\n  | jq --arg u \"$E\" -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'\n```\nAlternatively, for a more direct positive proof, add: `rebar verify-identity \"$E\"` (or equivalent) and assert exit 0.","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"na","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"broken_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"high","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"high","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Fix the AC2 jq proving command to expand the shell variable: replace `--arg u E` with `--arg u \"$E\"` (or `--argjson`/process substitution) so `$u` holds the actual event UUID, not the literal string \"E\".","cohort":["T3"],"criteria":["T3"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan text: `jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` — `--arg u E` assigns jq variable $u the literal four-character string \"E\"","jq --arg syntax: `--arg name value` takes two positional whitespace-separated tokens; shell variable expansion does not occur inside jq argument parsing","verify_identity_report.schema.json line 8: `event_uuid` confirmed as a real UUID string field — never equal to the literal \"E\"","Prior plan-review cache entries (4dc0, 1a51) independently flag this same mismatch, confirming it is not a one-off inference","Evidence class: Contradicted — the command as written cannot perform its stated check"],"finding":"The AC2 proving command `jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'` is mechanically broken: jq's `--arg name value` syntax binds the literal token `E` (a four-character string) to `$u`, not the shell variable holding the actual event UUID. Because no real UUID equals the string \"E\", the `all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)` predicate trivially returns true and exits 0 for every possible input — it is a permanently vacuous check that cannot detect the case where event E actually does appear in the non-verified report.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f80d887127cd08701","impact":1.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC2, second bullet: `rebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u E -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'`","norm_id":"n235f9264c3c6942f","priority":1.0,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["Operator runs the AC2 proving command after a real run; it exits 0 even if the event IS present in the non-verified report (i.e., signing failed silently), giving false confidence that signing is working.","If the signed event is somehow mis-classified as non-verified, the check passes anyway — the story's entire end-to-end proof is invalidated."],"severity":"critical","suggested_fix":"Replace the proving command with:\n```sh\nE=\"<the recorded event uuid>\"\nrebar verify-identity --all --format json | jq --arg u \"$E\" -e 'all(.[]; .event_uuid != $u)'\n```\nThe double-quoted `\"$E\"` causes the shell to expand the variable before passing its value to jq's `--arg` parser.","tier":"LLM","validity":1.0,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"broken_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"high","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"high","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add an AC (or expand AC2) requiring the canary workflow (`reconcile-bridge-canary`) to independently produce and record a verified signed event — a workflow-run URL plus a `rebar verify-identity`-verified event uuid — so the leaf fully delivers what the parent's story 2 specifies ('reconcile-bridge **and its canary**').","cohort":["G7"],"criteria":["G7"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Parent dc09 story-2 text: 'GitHub Actions signing — populate the `REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY` secret and confirm `reconcile-bridge` (and its canary) produce signed events on a real run.'","Leaf AC2: 'A CI run produces a signed, verified bot event. A `reconcile-bridge` run writes ≥1 event authored by `594c`.' — canary is only mentioned as an alternative proof path in the What section, not as an independent AC.","Leaf Scope: 'The GitHub Actions workflows that write tickets (reconcile-bridge + its canary)' — lists both but only reconcile-bridge gets an explicit signed-event AC.","ABSENCE: no AC in the leaf requires the canary workflow to independently produce and record a verified signed event."],"finding":"The parent epic (dc09) specifies story 2 as confirming that both 'reconcile-bridge (and its canary)' produce signed events on a real run. The leaf's ACs only require a reconcile-bridge run to produce a signed event; no AC independently requires the canary workflow to produce a separately confirmed, verified signed event.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"faeac75fcd81073b2","impact":1.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Leaf Acceptance Criteria (AC2) vs. dc09 'Scope / planned child stories' item 2","norm_id":"nf5e54b113ae70adc","priority":0.875,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["A reconcile-bridge run produces a signed event and AC2 is marked satisfied, but the canary's signing has never been re-confirmed under dc09 — the parent's 'and its canary' requirement is silently dropped.","The canary's earlier signing proof (under 297d/1787) was for a different epic context; dc09 re-scopes the confirmation requirement, but the leaf does not carry that through to its ACs."],"severity":"critical","suggested_fix":"Add to AC2 (or as a separate AC): '[operator-attested] A `reconcile-bridge-canary` run produces ≥1 event authored by `594c`, confirmed verified via `rebar verify-identity --all --format json`; the workflow-run URL and signed event uuid are recorded on this ticket.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.875,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"yes","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"no","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"yes"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"missing_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"medium","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Either specify the canary write target and invocation (e.g. the workflow input flag or job name that triggers it, and how to retrieve the resulting event uuid), or state a concrete re-dispatch limit (e.g. 'after 3 runs with no delta, file a note and escalate') so the executor has a determinate termination condition.","cohort":["E2","E6","F1"],"criteria":["E2","E6","F1"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan text: 'If a given run has no inbound Jira delta to translate (so it writes no work-ticket event), re-dispatch until a run produces a bot-authored ticket event, or use the workflow's own canary write'","ABSENCE: no description of the canary write target, invocation command, or how to extract its event uuid for use in the AC2 proving commands.","This creates an open-ended 'keep trying' loop with no specified termination bound and an unspecified alternative path."],"finding":"The 'canary write' fallback — mentioned as the escape hatch when no Jira delta is available — is never specified: the plan does not name the canary target, how to invoke it, what event it produces, or how to obtain its event uuid `E`. An executor who runs several dispatches with no Jira delta has no actionable alternative to reach the AC.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f4eea01b111a4212e","impact":0.536,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section: 'or use the workflow's own canary write — the AC is satisfied by a real signed event id, not merely a green run.'","norm_id":"na80077f20ef0beab","priority":0.402,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["Jira has no pending delta at verification time; the executor re-dispatches several times, gets no bot-authored ticket event, and cannot proceed because the canary alternative is unnamed and uninvokable."],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.75,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"underspecified_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"medium"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify the canary write fallback: document what event the canary produces, confirm it runs under the bot identity `594c`, and show the exact commands to locate and verify its signed event uuid `E` so the AC proof path is unambiguous when no Jira delta arrives.","cohort":["E3","G5","T6"],"criteria":["E3"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["\"or use the workflow's own canary write — the AC is satisfied by a real signed event id, not merely a green run\"","The canary write mechanism is named but its behavior (what it writes, when it runs, how to extract its event uuid for verification) is not described anywhere in the plan.","The AC verification commands reference a ticket `<t>` and event uuid `E` but do not clarify how these are obtained from a canary write vs. a real Jira-delta write."],"finding":"The fallback proof path via 'the workflow's own canary write' is mentioned but not specified — it is unclear what the canary writes, whether it always runs, and how an operator would isolate and verify its signed event uuid, leaving the end-state-observable proof underspecified for the case where no Jira delta arrives.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fdaf9a5c472c78ce3","impact":0.536,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section / 'If a given run has no inbound Jira delta...' + AC second bullet","norm_id":"na151b91d947cfb16","priority":0.402,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["Operator triggers multiple reconcile-bridge runs but no Jira delta arrives during the verification window; operator attempts to use the canary path but cannot find the signed event uuid because canary behavior is undocumented.","Canary write turns out to always be unsigned or attributed to a different identity, silently invalidating the fallback proof path."],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"Add a note such as: 'The reconcile-bridge canary step writes a synthetic event of type `<canary-event-type>` on ticket `<canary-ticket-id>` authored by `594c`; retrieve its uuid with `rebar show <canary-ticket-id> --format json | jq -r \".events[-1].uuid\"` and run the same `rebar verify-identity` check.' If the canary does not run under the bot identity, note that and instruct the operator to wait for a real delta instead.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.75,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"underspecified_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"medium"}}},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Either specify the exact canary fallback procedure (which workflow to dispatch, what staleness condition triggers a write, how to locate the resulting ticket id and event uuid), or replace the vague canary mention with a concrete alternative such as a synthetic `rebar create` + `rebar close` via `workflow_dispatch` with a dedicated test input.","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["Plan text: 're-dispatch until a run produces a bot-authored ticket event, or use the workflow's own canary write'","reconcile-bridge-canary.yml: the canary's rebar writes only occur when staleness is detected (stale=true path) — it creates/updates a heartbeat-alert bug ticket; this is a conditional side-effect, not a guaranteed write","No procedure is given for identifying the canary-written ticket id or extracting its signed event uuid for use in the AC2 proving commands"],"finding":"The plan's fallback for when no Jira-delta run produces a bot-authored ticket event — 'use the workflow's own canary write' — is unspecified: it does not describe what event the canary writes, how to identify its ticket id or event uuid, or how to apply the AC2 proving commands to a canary-written event. The reconcile-bridge-canary only writes tickets when the reconciler is detected as stale, making it non-deterministic as a controlled fallback proving path.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f796e920e3e08d54c","impact":0.536,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section — 'or use the workflow's own canary write — the AC is satisfied by a real signed event id'","norm_id":"n25abae5e5ef6d638","priority":0.402,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["Operator repeatedly dispatches reconcile-bridge but Jira has no delta; operator falls back to canary, but the reconciler is healthy so canary writes nothing; operator has no path to AC satisfaction"],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"","tier":"LLM","validity":0.75,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"underspecified_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"medium"}}},{"block_threshold":0.6,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"","cohort":null,"criteria":["G6"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":[],"finding":"The 'use the workflow's own canary write' fallback path is imprecise: reconcile-bridge-canary.yml is a *separate* GitHub Actions workflow, not an internal step of reconcile-bridge. An implementer blocked on zero Jira-delta runs will be confused about what to dispatch and whether a canary-authored event satisfies the AC ('authored by identity 594c via reconcile-bridge').","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fe92d5ab1e3a56255","impact":0.536,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section — 'or use the workflow's own canary write'","norm_id":"n2d5759c138554850","priority":0.3685,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":[],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"In the What section replace 'use the workflow's own canary write' with 'dispatch the separate `reconcile-bridge-canary` workflow, which also reads `REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY` and writes via the rebar CLI with the bot email — canary-authored events are signed by identity 594c and satisfy the same AC.' Update AC2 to read 'a `reconcile-bridge` or `reconcile-bridge-canary` run writes ≥1 event authored by 594c.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.6875,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"na","cited_reference_accurate":"na","claims_absence":"na","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"no","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"insufficient"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"underspecified_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"medium"}}},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Clarify the fallback: name `reconcile-bridge-canary` explicitly (e.g., \"dispatch `reconcile-bridge-canary` which always writes a bot-authored event\") so the operator knows which workflow to trigger.","cohort":["G1G2"],"criteria":["G1G2"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["`.github/workflows/reconcile-bridge-canary.yml` is a distinct workflow file, not a step or job in `reconcile-bridge.yml`","Plan 'What' section: 'Trigger a `reconcile-bridge` run (`workflow_dispatch`…)'","Plan 'What' section fallback: 'or use the workflow's own canary write — the AC is satisfied by a real signed event id'","The canary writes events via `rebar` CLI calls in `reconcile-bridge-canary.yml`, not via the reconciler in `reconcile-bridge.yml`"],"finding":"The plan's fallback trigger instruction says \"use the workflow's own canary write\", but the canary is a separate workflow (`reconcile-bridge-canary.yml`), not a step inside `reconcile-bridge.yml`. The Scope section lists both workflows, but the What/trigger paragraph only mentions dispatching `reconcile-bridge`. An operator following the plan's primary instruction may not know to separately dispatch `reconcile-bridge-canary` or understand which workflow produces the canary-written ticket event.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f44c8e035e069cf01","impact":0.536,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section — \"or use the workflow's own canary write\"; Scope section — \"reconcile-bridge + its canary\"","norm_id":"n67d80f4465eac8b3","priority":0.335,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["Operator dispatches `reconcile-bridge` but it produces no Jira-delta events; they then look for 'the workflow's own canary write' in that workflow but find none — the canary is a separate workflow that must be separately triggered."],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"In the 'What' section replace \"or use the workflow's own canary write\" with \"or dispatch `reconcile-bridge-canary` (a separate workflow that always writes a bot-authored ticket event) to guarantee a signed event for verification\".","tier":"LLM","validity":0.625,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"no","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"underspecified_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"medium","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"medium"}}},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Add an explicit rollback/recovery step: state that if the new secret produces verification failures, the operator should re-fetch from SSM (`aws ssm get-parameter --name /rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key --with-decryption`) and re-run `gh secret set` — and add a pre-flight check (e.g., validate the SSM key's public half matches the registered key on identity 594c before setting the secret).","cohort":["COH","E1","T4"],"criteria":["T4"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'Because a GitHub secret value cannot be read back, this story re-sets it from the authoritative SSM source' — acknowledges irreversibility but provides no recovery path","No rollback or back-out step is described anywhere in the plan","If the SSM value is stale or incorrect, CI signing breaks and the prior secret value cannot be restored from GitHub"],"finding":"The re-set of `REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY` overwrites a write-only secret (the old value is permanently unreadable from GitHub), but the plan states no explicit rollback/back-out path for the case where the SSM-sourced key is incorrect or the set produces a broken signing state.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f065df51e0e05a7f2","impact":0.264,"is_primary":null,"location":"Precondition section / What section — 'gh secret set REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY --repo navapbc/rebar fed the decrypted SSM value'","norm_id":"nce082e3190a8952c","priority":0.165,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["SSM `/rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key` holds a rotated or mismatched key not yet registered on identity 594c — after the set, CI produces unsigned or invalid events and the previous (possibly correct) secret is gone","Operator fat-fingers the `gh secret set` pipeline, setting an empty or truncated value — no stated procedure to detect and recover"],"severity":"minor","suggested_fix":"Add a 'Rollback' subsection under 'What': 'If AC #2 fails (no verified event after two dispatch attempts), recovery is: (1) re-fetch the key from SSM with decryption, (2) validate its public half matches the ed25519 key registered on identity 594c (`rebar show-identity 594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d`), (3) re-run `gh secret set`. The SSM parameter is the authoritative source and is always recoverable.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.625,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"no","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"yes","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"low","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"moderate","silent_vs_self_revealing":"self_revealing","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Define a concrete fallback trigger for the canary write path (e.g., 'if two consecutive dispatches produce no ticket event, use the workflow's canary write instead') and specify what the canary write AC evidence looks like so the verification loop has a bounded exit condition.","cohort":["T12","T5b","T9"],"criteria":["T5b"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["'re-dispatch until a run produces a bot-authored ticket event, or use the workflow's own canary write' — 'or use the canary write' is mentioned as an alternative but not specified as a fallback trigger, leaving the primary path open-ended","No timeout or escalation (e.g., 'after N dispatches, escalate to...') is stated"],"finding":"The plan specifies 're-dispatch until a run produces a bot-authored ticket event' with no maximum retry count, timeout, or escalation path if the reconcile-bridge workflow consistently runs without producing a translatable Jira delta.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f0d205c5c6fd0e7e9","impact":0.55,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section: 'If a given run has no inbound Jira delta to translate...re-dispatch until a run produces a bot-authored ticket event'","norm_id":"n9f288e6fac97f957","priority":0.2063,"reason":"low-validity","scenarios":["Jira delta is consistently empty for an extended period; operator dispatches multiple times with no signed event produced; story never reaches AC closure","The canary write path is not clearly defined as a definitive fallback, so operators may not know when to switch to it"],"severity":"major","suggested_fix":"Add to the 'What' section: 'If two consecutive workflow_dispatch runs produce no bot-authored ticket event due to empty Jira delta, the canary write mechanism is used as the proving event; document the canary event uuid as the AC artifact.' This gives operators a clear decision point.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.375,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"no","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"no","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"no","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"underspecified_oracle","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"low"}}},{"block_threshold":0.7,"blocking_enabled":true,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Replace `rebar show <t> | jq -e '.authorship.signed >= 1'` with a correct proof command that targets an existing field — either inspect the raw event file on the tickets branch for `author_sig`, or use `rebar verify-identity --all --format json` as the sole proof and drop the `rebar show` step.","cohort":["T8"],"criteria":["T8"],"decision":"dropped","drop_reason":null,"evidence":["AC2 states: `rebar show <t> | jq -e '.authorship.signed >= 1'` (signature present)","ticket_state.schema.json: no `authorship` property defined; `additionalProperties: true` but the field is absent from `properties` and from the schema description","`_seam.py:301`: signing writes `event['author_sig'] = dsse.encode(...)` on the raw event dict, not on compiled state","reads_cli.py `_cmd_show` returns `show_state(...)` — the reducer's compiled projection, which does not aggregate `author_sig` occurrences into an `.authorship.signed` count"],"finding":"AC2's first proving command references `.authorship.signed` on `rebar show` output, but this field does not exist in the compiled ticket state. The `ticket_state.schema.json` has no `authorship` property; the seam writes `author_sig` onto the raw event dict, not the compiled state returned by `rebar show`. The jq path `.authorship.signed >= 1` will evaluate to `false` (null >= 1) on any real `rebar show` output, silently failing the proof.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f02a8c6882774a73d","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Acceptance Criteria — AC2: 'A CI run produces a signed, verified bot event' — `rebar show <t> | jq -e '.authorship.signed >= 1'`","norm_id":"nf274ee2fd44202bf","priority":0.0,"reason":"veto:cited-reference-inaccurate","scenarios":["Operator runs the AC2 proving command; jq evaluates `.authorship.signed` as null, `null >= 1` is false in jq, command exits non-zero and the AC appears to fail even on a correctly signed event","Alternatively jq exits 1 silently and the operator misdiagnoses a signing failure when the signing actually worked"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Use the event file directly: `git -C .tickets-tracker show origin/tickets:<ticket_dir>/<event_file>.json | jq -e '.author_sig != null'`. Alternatively rely solely on the absence-from-non-verified-report check already in AC2, which is correctly grounded.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.1667,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"no","cited_reference_accurate":"no","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"no","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"na","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"no","path_reachable":"no","respects_artifact_altitude":"na","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"none","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify the IAM principal (role or policy) and minimum permissions (`ssm:GetParameter` on `/rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key` only, plus `kms:Decrypt` on the SSM KMS key) the operator must assume when fetching the signing key from SSM, so the provisioning step is least-privilege and auditable.","cohort":["T10"],"criteria":["T10"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":"novelty","evidence":["Plan states: 'gh secret set REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY --repo navapbc/rebar fed the decrypted SSM value; never echoed' — but specifies no IAM role, policy, or credential scope for the operator's SSM read.","The EC2 instance role (ADR-0012) covers runtime reads by the box, not operator workstation sessions.","The same gap was flagged in cached reviews for story 79da: `.rebar/cache/plan-review/79da-c7e4-8d7c-471d/8add58af134fb96ce9a5.json` — 'The IAM principal and policy used to read the SSM SecureString /rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key are nowhere specified.'","ABSENCE: No mention of `ssm:GetParameter`, a named IAM role/policy, or instruction to use a scoped assume-role for this human operator step."],"finding":"The plan does not specify the IAM principal or minimum permission scope an operator must use to fetch `/rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key` from AWS SSM during the provisioning step. Without this, an operator may authenticate with overly broad credentials (e.g., AdministratorAccess or a personal IAM user with wide permissions) to run `aws ssm get-parameter`, violating least-privilege.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"f261b2dc4db92a7c6","impact":0.33,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section — 'Re-set the `REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY` GitHub Actions secret … fed the decrypted SSM value'","norm_id":"nd488a3766a9cd3cb","priority":0.165,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["Operator uses personal IAM user with AdministratorAccess to retrieve the signing key — audit trail shows a broad identity fetching a production private key.","Operator uses a CI deploy role with broad SSM read (`/rebar/prod/*`) rather than a tightly scoped single-param read, inconsistent with least-privilege."],"severity":"minor","suggested_fix":"Add a note to the 'Re-set' step: 'Authenticate to AWS using a role/policy limited to `ssm:GetParameter` on `arn:aws:ssm:<region>:<account>:parameter/rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key` and `kms:Decrypt` on the AWS-managed SSM KMS key. Do not use AdministratorAccess or a wildcard SSM read policy.' Reference the existing scoped instance role as the model.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.5,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"no","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"no","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"low"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Specify the safe SSM-to-GitHub piping mechanism in the plan's 'Re-set' step (e.g., direct stdin pipe: `aws ssm get-parameter --with-decryption --query Parameter.Value --output text --name /rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key | gh secret set REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY --repo navapbc/rebar --body -`), and note any shell-history precautions (e.g., `HISTFILE=/dev/null` prefix), so 'never echoed' is a verifiable mechanism not just an intent.","cohort":["T5c"],"criteria":["T5c"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":"novelty","evidence":["Plan phrase: 'gh secret set REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY --repo navapbc/rebar fed the decrypted SSM value; never echoed' — intent stated, mechanism unspecified","The asset is a long-lived ed25519 private key crossing the operator-shell boundary between AWS SSM and the GitHub API","ABSENCE: no example pipeline command, no stdin-pipe instruction, no shell-history mitigation (e.g., HISTFILE=/dev/null) specified"],"finding":"The plan's 'Re-set' step names the `gh secret set` command and asserts the value is 'never echoed,' but does not declare a safe piping mechanism for transferring the decrypted SSM SecureString to `gh secret set`. Without an explicit stdin-pipe pattern (e.g., `aws ssm get-parameter … | gh secret set --body -`), an implementer may store the key in a shell variable or use `--body \"$(aws …)\"`, transiently exposing the private key in shell history, process arguments, or shell-environment dumps.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fcf71f7bf8c5335b1","impact":0.33,"is_primary":null,"location":"What section — 'Re-set' bullet: 'gh secret set REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY --repo navapbc/rebar fed the decrypted SSM value; never echoed'","norm_id":"n7d8b628e64a1a484","priority":0.165,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["Operator runs `VALUE=$(aws ssm get-parameter --with-decryption --query Parameter.Value --output text --name /rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key); gh secret set REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY --body \"$VALUE\"` — key appears in shell history and process list.","Shell debug mode (`set -x`) active in operator's session leaks the key to terminal output or a log file."],"severity":"minor","suggested_fix":"In the 'What / Re-set' bullet, replace the implicit 'fed the decrypted SSM value' with an explicit inline pipeline: `aws ssm get-parameter --with-decryption --query Parameter.Value --output text --name /rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key | gh secret set REBAR_BOT_SIGNING_KEY --repo navapbc/rebar --body -`. Add a note that the operator should prefix with `HISTFILE=/dev/null` or use a subshell that avoids history recording.","tier":"LLM","validity":0.5,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"no","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"no","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"none","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"low"}}},{"block_threshold":0.95,"blocking_enabled":false,"checklist_item":"- [ ] Document the key-rotation re-sync procedure (e.g., re-run the `gh secret set` step from SSM whenever the bot key is rotated) and note where this procedure lives (runbook, ADR-0012, or this ticket) so future rotations do not silently degrade CI signing.","cohort":["T12","T5b","T9"],"criteria":["T9"],"decision":"advisory","drop_reason":"novelty","evidence":["The plan introduces a two-copy state: SSM holds the canonical key, GitHub holds a derived copy set once by this story","No re-sync process, rotation hook, or staleness detection is mentioned","The plan's own proof-of-correctness relies on the downstream signed event, but a future rotation would silently break signing with no defined recovery path"],"finding":"The plan does not address the key-rotation / re-sync lifecycle between the authoritative SSM SecureString and the GitHub Actions secret copy: if the Rebar Bot's ed25519 key is rotated in SSM (and on the identity), the GitHub secret silently becomes stale and CI reverts to unsigned writes without any alert or re-sync trigger.","group_criteria":null,"group_id":null,"id":"fc555b73a5feba01b","impact":0.0,"is_primary":null,"location":"Precondition section: 'The private key is available from AWS SSM SecureString /rebar/prod/rebar-bot-signing-key'","norm_id":"n38bfd4c7fd6b84b0","priority":0.0,"reason":"default-advisory","scenarios":["Bot key is rotated for security reasons; SSM is updated; GitHub secret is not re-synced; CI silently reverts to unsigned writes; no alert fires; this story's AC does not cover future rotations"],"severity":"none","suggested_fix":"Add a 'Key Rotation' note to the Scope or Precondition section: 'If the Rebar Bot key is rotated in SSM, re-run the `gh secret set` command from the updated SSM value and trigger a verification run. Document this re-sync step in the runbook referenced by ADR-0012.'","tier":"LLM","validity":0.625,"verification":{"binary":{"absence_confirmed_in_context":"yes","cited_reference_accurate":"yes","claims_absence":"yes","committed_work_relies_on_unbacked_claim":"na","evidence_entails_finding":"yes","impact_follows_necessarily":"no","is_verifiable":"yes","no_existing_mitigation":"yes","no_viable_alternative_explanation":"yes","path_reachable":"yes","respects_artifact_altitude":"no","severity_claim_justified":"no"},"severity_attributes":{"ac_unverifiable":"none","blast_radius":"local","debt_impact":"low","divergent_implementation":"none","dod_uncertifiable":"none","internal_conflict":"none","irreversible_without_rationale":"none","likelihood":"low","prod_impact":"low","reversibility":"easy","silent_vs_self_revealing":"silent","undecomposed":"none","vague_directive":"none"}}}],"impact_model_version":"plan-v3","material_fingerprint":"f0a14ce0fa650faf","metrics":{"claim_path":"no-llm/no-network (structural; the fast claim check is a local HMAC verify)","det_ms":240.2,"llm_calls":29,"llm_ms":445268.7,"total_ms":445